  "body": "Paper:\r\nhttps://nsg.ee.ethz.ch/fileadmin/user_upload/publications/perimeter.pdf\r\nTalk:\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VCGyZADm_aQ\r\n\r\ntl;dr:\r\nThis paper PERIMETER from Financial Cryptography and Data Security 2021 claimed that the behavior of devp2p in ETH 1.0 clients could cause the TXs from certain user to be associated with that exact user's ip address. \r\n\r\nAlthough we already have transport layer encryption [(rlpx)](https://github.com/ethereum/devp2p/blob/master/rlpx.md) from devp2p in ETH 1.0, traffic analysis can be applied as claimed by PERIMETER. \r\n\r\nAs far as I know, the p2p interface in ETH 2.0 is more close to libp2p rather than devp2p. \r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/dev/specs/phase0/p2p-interface.md\r\n\r\nDoes the noise protocol used by libp2p have the appropriate security features to deal with the traffic analysis issues found by PERIMETER? \r\nOr, is the issue in the paper actually a *non-issue*, in a sense that it doesn't matter in the broad picture?\r\n\r\nAll in all, just a FYI as I myself would also like the clients to be more secure in ETH 2.0. \r\n: P",
